The specific grounds on which she was barred entry to the US have not been confirmed. And it is not known if she was stopped at passport control or at the departure gate where passports are often scanned.

Today, a US embassy spokesman said: 'There are several ways of legally travelling into the United States and Ms Lawson has been invited to come to the embassy and apply for a visa for travel to the U.S.

'We understand she has professional requirements for US travel and these matters are generally handled routinely and expeditiously, so stand by.'

The spokesman said the embassy was unable to comment on the reasons that someone might be turned away.

